properties.updateMessage: Provide narrower definition which focuses on primary anxiety for long covid analysis.
properties.provenance:
Provide a narrower definition which focuses on primary anxiety for long covid analysis.

Only took descendants of "Anxiety Disorder" and removed secondary forms of anxiety and conditions where the primary pathology was depression. Additionally removed conditions where they were unlikely to be related to Long Covid such as Stockholm syndrome. Phobias that are descendants of "Anxiety Disorder" were included in the concept set.
properties.limitations: This term was created without consult or consensus from a multiple members of a domain team or working group.

properties.issues:
In the outpatient context, here is very little precision in how the codes are used.
In the inpatient context, anyone with coma has, by definition, complicated diabetes, even if the code itself sounds non-chronic.
properties.intention: Create broad and generic general use concept as starting place for research teams and for use in calculating comorbidity indices.  Intent is to only include codes that are specific to this comorbidity category.  Notion of "complicated" (or not) is based on the intention of the Charlson definition of "diabetes with chronic complications."
properties.provenance: Selected parent SNOMED-CT condition and included descendants (standard codes only).  Apply clinical review result, removed concepts that should not be included.  Incorporates domain team feedback.
properties.limitations: May not include certain medications or procedures that may signal a condition. Also note that only standard concepts are included, so should be applied to only the harmonized data. Includes acute complications and other manifestations of diabetes that do not fit in Charlson's notion of "chronic complication". So "uncomplicated" may still be clinically complicated.

properties.intention: Clinical Focus: Evidence of a hematopoietic stem cell transplant (HSCT) (i.e., bone marrow transplant) in the patient record.; Data Element Scope: Evidence that a HSCT has been performed on the patient. Since SNOMED CT does not provide disorder codes for HSCT, this VS only consists of "disorder" codes that represent complications of HSCT.; Inclusion Criteria: SNOMED CT disorder codes that represent complications of HSCTs (regardless of the type of bone marrow/stem cell transplant). Active and inactive codes since inactive codes are not always updated in a patient record.

properties.issues: In the outpatient context, there is very little precision in how the codes are used. In the inpatient context, anyone with coma has, by definition, complicated diabetes, even if the code itself sounds non-chronic.
properties.intention: Create broad and generic general use concept as a starting place for research teams and for use in calculating comorbidity indices. Intent is to only include codes that are specific to this comorbidity category. Notion of "complicated" (or not) is based on the intention of the Charlson definition of "diabetes with chronic complications."
properties.provenance: Selected parent SNOMED-CT condition and included descendants (standard codes only). /Exclude concept set expression item not considered complicated from the clinical review. Incorporates input from domain team
properties.limitations: May not include certain medications or procedures that may signal a condition. Also note that only standard concepts are included, so should be applied to only the harmonized data. Notion of "complicated" was taken in the sense of Charlson's "chronic" complications.

However, many patients living with HIV are identified solely by medication or lab records, i.e., those lacking concurrent diagnosis codes. Therefore, this set is not recommended for identifying a cohort of people living with HIV. properties.intention: Create broad and generic general use concept as starting place for research teams and for use in calculating comorbidity indices.  Inclusive of thalassemia diagnoses that are clinically relevant to the proband patient
properties.provenance: Based on the SNOMED (OMOP) hierarchy for thalassemia plus comparison with other Enclave concept sets to locate any missing concepts.  Confirmed no relevant standard SNOMED Observations. Reviewed by Hematology Domain Team.
properties.limitations: Excludes patients with thalassemia traits (heterozygotes), with sickle cell disease and with other beta chain hemoglobinopathies, like C and D. Dividing thalassemia into transfusion-dependent, severe, or otherwise requires a phenotype definition taking into account hemoglobin levels, electrophoresis or transfusion experience.
